or]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])}}\n}}\n'''Frederick Stephen''' \"'''Fred'''\" '''Upton''' (born April 23, 1953) is the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for {{ushr|MI|6}}, serving since 1987. He is a member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] and Chairman of the [[United States House Committee on Energy and Commerce|Committee on Energy and Commerce]]. The district stretches along the Michigan-[[Indiana]] border in the southwestern part of the state.\n\n==Early life, education, and early political career==\nUpton was born in [[St. Joseph, Michigan]], the son of Elizabeth B. (n\u00e9e Vial) and Stephen Edward Upton.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~battle/reps/upton.htm |title=Frederick Stephen Upton |publisher=rootsweb.ancestry.com |date= |accessdate=February 21, 2012}}</ref> Upton attended [[Shattuck-Saint Mary's|Shattuck School]] in [[Faribault, Minnesota]], graduating in 1971.<ref>[http://www.nndb.com/people/862/000040742/]</ref> Upton earned a [[Bachelor's degree|B.A.]] in journalism from the [[University of Michigan]] in 1975. He was a member of the [[Alpha Delta Phi]] Fraternity, Peninsular Chapter and became a sports editor at ''[[The Michigan Daily]]'' and thought he might someday cover the [[Chicago Cubs]].<ref name=\"wapo\">{{cite news|last=Will|first=George F.|title=Fred Upton, Rust Belt revolutionary|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2011/01/07/AR2011010703152.html|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=January 9, 2011}}</ref> He served on the congressional staff of U.S. Congressman [[David Stockman]] (R-MI) from 1976 to 1980. He was in the [[Office of Management and Budget]] (OMB) under [[Ronald Reagan]] from 1981 to 1985, while Stockman served as OMB Director.\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===Elections===\n'''1986'''\n\nA protege of OMB director and former U.S. Congressman David Stockman, he ran in [[Michigan's 4th congressional district]] against incumbent Republican U.S. Congressman [[Mark Siljander]], Stockman's successor. Upton won the Republican [[Primary election|primary]] 55%\u201345%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=223545 |title=MI District 4 \u2013 R Primary Race \u2013 Aug 05, 1986 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=February 21, 2012}}</ref> He won the general election with 62% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=52363 |title=MI District 4 Race \u2013 Nov 04, 1986 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=February 21, 2012}}</ref>\n\n'''1988'''\n\nUpton won re-election to a second term with 71% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=37667 |title=MI District 4 Race \u2013 Nov 08, 1988 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=February 21, 2012}}</ref>\n\n'''1990'''\n\nHe faced a challenge in the Republican primary by Ed Fredericks, ultimately defeating Fredericks by a margin of 63%\u201337%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=514490 |title=MI District 4 \u2013 R Primary Race \u2013 Aug 07, 1990 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=February 21, 2012}}</ref> In the general election, he won re-election to a third term with 58% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=34075 |title=MI District 4 Race \u2013 Nov 06, 1990 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=February 21, 2012}}</ref>\n\n'''1992\u20132000'''\n\nAfter redistricting, Upton decided to run in the newly redrawn [[Michigan's 6th congressional district]], winning re-election in 1992 to a fourth term with 62% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=28013 |title=MI District 6 Race \u2013 Nov 03, 1992 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=February 21, 2012}}</ref> During this time period, he didn't have a Republican challenger and never won re-election with less than 62%.\n\n'''2002'''\n\nAfter redistricting, Upton faced a primary challenge from state senator [[Dale Shugars]]. Upton defeated Shugars 66%\u201332%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=481481 |title=MI District 6 \u2013 R Primary Race \u2013 Aug 06, 2002 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=February 21, 2012}}</ref> He won the general election with 69% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=1167 |title=MI District 6 Race \u2013 Nov 05, 2002 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=February 21, 2012}}</ref>\n\n'''2004'''\n\nUpton defeated [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] Scott Elliott, an art gallery owner, 65%\u201332%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=4188 |title=MI \u2013 District 06 Race \u2013 Nov 02, 2004 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=February 21, 2012}}</ref>\n\n'''2006'''\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Michigan, 2006#District 6}}\nUpton defeated Democrat [[Kim Clark (candidate)|Kim Clark]] 61%\u201338%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=206962 |title=MI \u2013 District 06 Race \u2013 Nov 07, 2006 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=February 21, 2012}}</ref>\n\n'''2008'''\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Michigan, 2008#District 6}}\nUpton defeated Democrat [[Don Cooney]], a Kalamazoo City Commissioner, 59%\u201339%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=387989 |title=MI \u2013 District 06 Race \u2013 Nov 04, 2008 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=February 21, 2012}}</ref>\n\n'''2010'''\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Michigan, 2010#District 6}}\nUpton was challenged in the Republican primary by former State Representative [[Jack Hoogendyk]]. Upton defeated him 57%\u201343%.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/local/wire/chi-ap-mi-ushouse-6thdistri,0,6356344.story |title=Elections : Elections News and Photos |publisher=Chicago Tribune |date= |accessdate=2010-08-23}} {{Dead link|date=April 2011|bot=RjwilmsiBot}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=646530 |title=MI District 06 \u2013 R Primary Race \u2013 Aug 03, 2010 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=February 21, 2012}}</ref> In the general election, he defeated Cooney in a rematch 62%\u201334%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=496769 |title=MI \u2013 District 06 Race \u2013 Nov 02, 2010 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=February 21, 2012}}</ref>\n\n'''2012'''\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Michigan, 2012#District 6}}\nIn 2011, Hoogendyk met with the [[Club for Growth]], a fiscally conservative [[501(c) organization|501(c)4]] organization, about running against Upton in a rematch in 2012.<ref>{{cite news|last=Toeplitz|first=Shira|title=Club for Growth Encouraging Upton Primary Challenger|url=http://www.rollcall.com/news/club_for_growth_encouraging_upton_primary_challenger-209999-1.html|newspaper=Roll Call|date=November 2, 2011}}</ref> Upton has been criticized for not being [[Conservatism in the United States|conservative]] enough by [[Rush Limbaugh]], [[Glenn Beck]], [[FreedomWorks]], Right to Life of Michigan, and the Southwest Michigan [[Tea Party Patriots]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Samuelsohn |first=Darren |last2=Dobias |first2=Matt |url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0112/71347.html |title=Fred Upton still faces arrows from the right |publisher=[[Politico]] |date=January 11, 2012 |accessdate=February 21, 2012}}</ref> On January 17, 2012, Hoogendyk announced that he would challenge Upton in the primary, the winner of which would face Democrat [[Mike O'Brien (Michigan politician)|Mike O'Brien]] in the general election.<ref>{{cite web|first=Fritz |last=Klug |url=http://www.mlive.com/news/kalamazoo/index.ssf/2012/01/jack_hoogendyk_to_again_challe.html |title=Jack Hoogendyk to challenge U.S. Rep. Fred Upton again for seat in Congress |publisher=Kalamazoo Gazette |date=January 17, 2012 |accessdate=February 21, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Coeman|first=Zak|title=Democrat Campaigns for House|url=http://www.westernherald.com/news/democrat-campaigns-for-house/|accessdate=4 June 2012|newspaper=[[Western Herald]]}}</ref> Upton defeated Hoogendyk in the August 2012 Republican primary, advancing to the general election in November.<ref>http://www.wsbt.com/news/wsbt-upton-defeats-hoogendyk-again-in-gop-primary-20120807,0,3817147.story</ref>\n\nWhile initial polls showed Upton with a sizable lead over the challenger, former [[Marine (military)|marine]] and businessman Mike O'Brien, a poll in October showed Upton and O'Brien locked in a statistical \"dead-heat\" heading into the final stretch of the campaign.<ref>{{cite web|title=House Race Ratings|url=http://elections.nytimes.com/2012/ratings/house|publisher=New York Times|accessdate=13 October 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Klug|first=Fritz|title=Southwest Michigan Politics: Mike O'Brien poll shows challenger in 'dead heat' with Congressman Fred Upton|url=http://www.mlive.com/news/kalamazoo/index.ssf/2012/10/southwest_michigan_politics_mi_1.html|publisher=MLive|accessdate=13 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n'''2014'''\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Michigan, 2014#District 6}}\n\n'''2016'''\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Michigan, 2016#District 6}}\n\nUpton won re election in 2016, defeating democratic challenger, Mark Clement 58.48%-36.41%, gaining a total of 193,259 votes, compared to Clements 119,980 votes\n\n===Tenure===\nUpton has been a member of moderate Republican factions [[The Tuesday Group (of moderate Republican congressmen)|The Tuesday Group]] and the [[Republican Main Street Partnership]].{{citation needed|date=April 2013}}\n\n'''Healthcare'''\n\nUpton voted against passage of the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]] (PPACA) and has since voted in favor of its complete repeal, stating that the law ignored the will of the people and that a bill that important should not have been passed without strong [[bipartisan]] support.{{Clarify|date=December 2011}}  Upton also believes that with [[United States public debt|the current level of debt]], the United States cannot afford the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act|PPACA]].{{Citation needed|date=April 2012}}\nIn November 2013, in response to Americans losing their [[health insurance]] coverage because of the [[Affordable Care Act]], Upton proposed a bill what would allow them to retain their health insurance coverage.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Parker |first1=Ashley |last2=Shear |first2=Michael D. |date=November 13, 2013 |title=With Enrollment Slow, Some Democrats Back Change in Health Law |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2013/11/14/us/politics/democrats-threaten-to-abandon-obama-on-health-law-provision.html?hpw&rref=us&_r=0 |newspaper=New York Times |accessdate=November 14, 2013 |subscription=Yes |quote=In addition, a vote is scheduled Friday in the Republican-controlled House on a bill that would allow Americans to keep their existing health coverage through 2014 without penalties. The measure, drafted by Representative Fred Upton, the Michigan Republican who is the chairman of the Energy and Commerce Committee, is opposed by the White House, which argues that it would severely undermine the Affordable Care Act by allowing insurance companies to continue to sell health coverage that does not meet the higher standard of Mr. Obama\u2019s health care law. }}</ref>  The essence of the Upton bill is to allow insurance companies to maintain their current individual insurance market policies according to state insurance rules that are in effect as of 2013.<ref>{{cite news |last=Capretta |first=James C. |date=November 13, 2013 |title=The Upton Bill Is No Small Matter |url=http://www.weeklystandard.com/author/james-c.-capretta |newspaper=The Weekly Standard |location=Washington, D.C. |accessdate=November 14, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nOn September 27, 2013, Upton introduced the [[Drug Quality and Security Act (H.R. 3204; 113th Congress)]], a bill that would grant the [[Food and Drug Administration]] more power to regulate drug [[compounding]] in the wake of the [[New England Compounding Center meningitis outbreak]].<ref name=senateinches>{{cite news|last=Cox|first=Ramsey|title=Senate inches toward passing drug bill|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/floor-action/senate/190254-senate-inches-toward-passing-drug-bill|accessdate=15 November 2013|newspaper=The Hill|date=14 November 2013}}</ref> Upton indicated that 3 of those who died were in his district.<ref name=uptonPR>{{cite web|title=House Passes Upton Bill to Prevent Repeat of Deadly Meningitis Outbreak, Strengthen Prescription Drug Supply Chain|url=http://upton.house.gov/news/documentsingle.aspx?DocumentID=351658|publisher=Office of Representative Upton|accessdate=15 November 2013|date=September 28, 2013}}</ref> The bill passed in the House and was being debated in the Senate.\n\n'''Environment'''\n\nUpton's website once stated: \"I strongly believe that everything must be on the table as we seek to reduce [[carbon emissions]].\"<ref name=MoJo>Sheppard, Kate (2011-01-04) [http://motherjones.com/blue-marble/2011/01/fred-upton-global-warming Fred Upton's Climate Changeup], ''[[Mother Jones (magazine)|Mother Jones]]''</ref> In April 2009, he maintained that \"[[climate change]] is a serious problem that necessitates serious solutions. Everything must be on the table.\"<ref>[http://www.rivercountryjournal.com/?p=7369 Upton hails KVCC wind energy program as Congress debates climate change bill], ''River Country Journal''{{Who|date=August 2011}} (April 24, 2009)</ref> However, \"Upton has gradually retreated from his moderate stance on climate change and carbon emissions.\"<ref name=MoJo/> In late 2010, he co-authored a ''[[Wall Street Journal]]'' editorial saying he was \"not convinced\" that \"carbon is a problem in need of regulation,\" and urging [[United States Congress|Congress]] to overturn [[Massachusetts v. Environmental Protection Agency]]. (See [[Regulation of greenhouse gases under the Clean Air Act]])<ref>{{cite news| url=http://online.wsj.com/article/SB10001424052748703929404576022070069905318.html?mod=WSJ_Opinion_LEFTTopOpinion | work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] | first1=Fred | last1=Upton | first2=Tim | last2=Phillips | title=How Congress Can Stop the EPA's Power Grab | date=December 28, 2010}}</ref> He is the co-sponsor, with [[Ed Whitfield]], of the \u201cEnergy Tax Prevention Act of 2011\u201d.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hawkins |first=Dave |url=http://switchboard.nrdc.org/blogs/dhawkins/dirty_air_extremism.html |title=Dirty Air Extremism |work=Switchboard |publisher=[[Natural Resources Defense Council]] |date=February 9, 2011 |accessdate=February 21, 2012}}</ref>\n\nRegarding the [[regulation of greenhouse gases under the Clean Air Act]] being upheld in Federal Appeals court, Upton said that Congress\u2019s refusal to approve [[greenhouse gas]] limits constituted a decision and that lawmakers should act now to reverse the [[United States Environmental Protection Agency]] emissions rules. Carbon regulation \u201cthreatens to drive energy prices higher, destroy jobs and hamstring our economic recovery,\u201d per Upton.  The [[Automotive industry in the United States|American automobile industry]] supports the regulations.<ref>[http://www.nytimes.com/2012/06/27/science/earth/epa-emissions-rules-backed-by-court.html Court Backs E.P.A. Over Emissions Limits Intended to Reduce Global Warming] June 26, 2012</ref>  Due to his environmental policies, the [[Los Angeles Times]] wrote in 2011 that Upton \"represents one of the biggest threats to planet Earth on planet Earth.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Year in Review: Congress' 10 biggest enemies of the Earth|url=http://opinion.latimes.com/opinionla/2011/12/republicans-environment.html|publisher=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=4 November 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007 Upton was a co-sponsor of the [[Energy Independence and Security Act of 2007]] which among other things mandated phased-in energy efficiency standards for most light bulbs. At the time, Upton noted that the legislation, ultimately signed into law by President George W. Bush, would \"help preserve energy resources and reduce harmful emissions, all while saving American families billions of dollars on their electric bills.\"<ref name=\"Time050913\">Grunwald, Michael [http://business.time.com/2013/05/09/long-live-the-lightbulb/ \"Long Live the Lightbulb. Big Government has made it better\"], Accessed May 21, 2012, ''Time'' magazine, May 20, 2013, p. Business-6</ref> But in 2010, after [[Glenn Beck]] called Upton \"all socialist\" for supporting the bill,<ref>[http://www.politico.com/news/stories/1110/45360.html \"Fred Upton to revisit light bulb ban\"], ''Politico'', November 18, 2010, Accessed May 21, 2013</ref> Upton led a failed effort to stop Obama from enforcing the new energy standards.<ref name=\"Time050913\"/>\n\n'''Energy'''\n\nOn October 22, 2013, Upton introduced the [[North American Energy Infrastructure Act (H.R. 3301; 113th Congress)]], a bill that would make changes to permitting requirements for pipelines and other energy infrastructure at international borders.<ref name=3301cbo>{{cite web|title=CBO \u2013 H.R. 3301|url=http://www.cbo.gov/publication/45400|publisher=Congressional Budget Office|accessdate=24 June 2014}}</ref><ref name=3301sum>{{cite web|title=H.R. 3301 \u2013 Summary|url=https://beta.congress.gov/bill/113th-congress/house-bill/3301|publisher=United States Congress|accessdate=25 June 2014}}</ref> Upton said that the bill \"is a sincere effort to focus a targeted solution to lessons learned from the Keystone pipeline... No one can rightly argue that the current presidential permit process as the State Department is not broken, no matter what side of the climate debate you're on.\"<ref name=WHthreatensCarna>{{cite news|last1=Carna|first1=Timothy|title=WH threatens veto of House oil pipeline bill|url=http://thehill.com/policy/energy-environment/210352-white-house-threatens-to-veto-houses-pipeline-bill|accessdate=26 June 2014|publisher=The Hill|date=24 June 2014}}</ref> Upton also argued that \"we're creating a fair and transparent approval process for cross-border energy projects, putting them all on a level playing field for the benefit of North American energy security, lower energy prices, and jobs.\"<ref name=PassutNGI>{{cite news|last1=Passut|first1=Charlie|title=House Passes Cross-Border Energy Infrastructure Bill|url=http://www.naturalgasintel.com/articles/98821-house-passes-cross-border-energy-infrastructure-bill|accessdate=26 June 2014|publisher=Natural Gas Intel|date=25 June 2014}}</ref>\n\n'''Video game content ratings'''\n\nOn September 29, 2006, Upton introduced the [[Video Game Decency Act]] ({{USBill|113|H.R.|6120}}) to the House during the [[109th United States Congress]].<ref name=6120sum>{{cite web|title=H.R. 6120 \u2013 Summary|url=http://beta.congress.gov/bill/109th-congress/house-bill/6120|publisher=United States Congress|accessdate=15 November 2013}}</ref> The bill was introduced and referred to the House Energy and Commerce Committee, but never received consideration. Upton reintroduced a bill by the same title ({{USBill|113|H.R.|1531}}) in the [[110th United States Congress]], which was also referred to that committee and never received a vote.<ref name=1531sum>{{cite web|title=H.R. 1531 \u2013 Summary|url=http://beta.congress.gov/bill/110th/house-bill/1531|publisher=United States Congress|accessdate=15 November 2013}}</ref>\n\n'''Abortion'''\n\nUpton generally supports pro-life legislation.<ref name=\"Project Vote Smart\">{{cite web|url=http://votesmart.org/npat.php?can_id=26906 |title=Project Vote Smart|publisher=[[votesmart.org]] |date= |accessdate=2010-11-24}}</ref>\n\n'''Gun laws'''\n\nUpton does not support restrictions on the purchase and possession of guns in most circumstances, and in 2010 received \"A\" and \"A-\" ratings from the [[National Rifle Association of America|National Rifle Association]] and the [[Gun Owners of America]], respectively.{{Citation needed|date=April 2012}} Upton supports some gun safety laws. From 1991-2003, Upton supported the interests of the [[Brady Campaign to Prevent Gun Violence]] 55 percent and in 1993, Upton supported a waiting period for gun purchase to provide background checks for criminal records.<ref name=\"Project Vote Smart\"/>\n\n'''LGBT issues'''\n\nUpton believes that marriage should be defined as between one man and one woman. Upton voted to propose an amendment to the Constitution regarding the definition of marriage on July 18, 2006.<ref name=\"Project Vote Smart\"/> He received a 15% rating from the Human Rights Campaign on LGBT Rights in 2008.<ref>''[http://www.hrc.org/documents/Congress_Scorecard-110th.pdf Congressional Scorecard]'', [[Human Rights Campaign]], 2008, p. 22.</ref>\n\n'''Fiscal issues'''\n\nUpton supports a [[balanced budget amendment|balanced-budget amendment to the Constitution]], a proposal that failed to acquire the two-thirds support necessary to pass the House in the [[112th Congress]]. Upton also supports the [[line-item veto]], which would authorize the President to propose the rescission of full or partial funding in a bill passed by Congress.\n\nIn the 111th session of Congress, Upton tabled $7,225,000 in federal funds through eleven earmarks,<ref>OpenSecrets.org. (n.d.). Fred Upton: Earmarks (fiscal year 2010). http://www.opensecrets.org/politicians/earmarks.php?cid=N00004133&cycle=2010</ref> but political pressure from inside of the Republican party led Upton to announce his support for a Republican initiative to install a moratorium in Congress on legislative earmarks to reduce unnecessary budget expenditures and the fiscal deficit.<ref>Bonyun, S.C. (2010, March 11). Upton urges all members to join effort banning earmarks. U.S. Congressman Fred Upton. http://upton.house.gov/news/documentsingle.aspx?DocumentID=191540</ref> According to the Council of Citizens Against Government Waste, a taxpayer watchdog group, Upton refrained from all earmarking activities during the 112th Congress.<ref>CCAGW. (2012). Pig book. http://www.cagw.org/reports/pig-book/2012/pork-database.html</ref>\n\nUpton has been criticized by the conservative website [[Human Events]] for being liberal with regards to fiscal issues.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hair|first=Connie|title=Connie Hair Upton's Shocking Votes on Energy-Related Bills|url=http://www.humanevents.com/article.php?id=40245|accessdate=5 March 2012}}</ref>  He has been recognized by the [[U.S. Chamber of Commerce]] with the \u201cSpirit of Enterprise\u201d award for \u201cstanding firmly against overreaching regulations and job-destroying mandates\u201d.<ref>{{cite news | author=Ken Paulman |title=Upton Honored by U.S. Chamber of Commerce |url=http://www.midwestenergynews.com/2011/03/31/upton-honored-by-u-s-chamber/ | work=Midwest Energy News | date=31 March 2011  |accessdate=2013-11-01 }}</ref>\n\nUpton introduced legislation to reverse the [[Federal Communication Commission|FCC's]] ruling on Net Neutrality in 2015.\n\n===Committee assignments===\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Energy and Commerce|Committee on Energy and Commerce]]''' (Chairman)\n** As Chairman of the full committee, Rep. Upton may serve as an [[Ex officio member|''ex officio'' member]] of all subcomittees. {{When|date=May 2011}}\n* '''[[United States Congress Joint Select Committee on Deficit Reduction|Joint Select Committee on Deficit Reduction]]'''\n\n===Caucus memberships===\n* Congressional Automotive Caucus<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kildee.house.gov/about/auto-caucus.shtml|title=Congressional Automotive Caucus|publisher=Congressman Dale Killdee|accessdate=2012-10-29}}</ref> (Co-Vice Chair)\n* Congressional Competitiveness Caucus<ref name=\"votesmart.org\">{{cite web|url=http://votesmart.org/candidate/biography/26906/fred-upton#.UIGTvlFKxrM|title=Representative Frederick 'Fred' Stephen Upton's Biography|publisher=Project Vote Smart|accessdate=2012-10-29}}</ref>\n* Congressional Travel and Tourism Caucus<ref name=\"votesmart.org\"/>\n* Diabetes Caucus<ref name=\"votesmart.org\"/>\n* India Caucus<ref name=\"votesmart.org\"/>\n* Indian-Americans Caucus<ref name=\"votesmart.org\"/>\n* [[United States Congressional International Conservation Caucus|International Conservation Caucus]]\n* Sportsmen's Caucus<ref name=\"votesmart.org\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\nUpton's grandfather, [[Frederick and Louis Upton|Frederick Upton]], was co-founder of appliance manufacturer and marketer [[Whirlpool Corporation]], which is headquartered in [[Benton Harbor, Michigan|Benton Harbor]]. His wife\u2019s name is Amey, and he has two children, Meg and Stephen.<ref name=\"pvs\"/> Upton's niece is supermodel [[Kate Upton]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Leach|first=Robin|title=Photos and videos: Kate Upton \u2014 from S.I. Rookie of the Year to cover girl.   if|url=http://www.lasvegassun.com/news/2012/feb/14/photos-and-videos-kate-upton-si-rookie-year-cover-/|newspaper=Las Vegas Sun|date=February 14, 2012}}</ref><ref>[http://www.weeklystandard.com/articles/meet-kate-upton-s-uncle_648832.html Meet Kate Upton\u2019s Uncle]; How a moderate Republican retooled for the [[Tea Party movement|Tea Party]] era, July 30, 2012, VOL. 17, NO. 43 [[Weekly Standard]]</ref> In 2014, [[Michigan Radio]] reported that Upton had a net worth of $7.3 million.<ref>[http://michiganradio.org/post/michigans-top-3-richest-and-poorest-members-congress#stream/0 Michigan's Top 3 Richest and Poorest Members of Congress]</ref>\n\nUpton is a supporter of [[Michigan Wolverines]] athletics as well as an enthusiastic [[Chicago Cubs]] baseball fan.<ref name=\"wapo\"/> He is a member of the [[Emil Verban]] Society.<ref name=\"pvs\">{{cite web|title=Representative Frederick 'Fred' Stephen Upton|url=http://votesmart.org/bio.php?can_id=26906|publisher=Project Vote Smart|accessdate=February 21, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Electoral history==\n{{s-start}}\n|+ {{ushr|Michigan|4|}}: Results 1986\u20131990<ref name=\"clerk\">{{cite web|url=http://clerk.house.gov/member_info/electionInfo/index.html |title=Office of the House Clerk \u2013 Electoral Statistics |publisher=Clerk of the United States House of Representatives |accessdate= |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080730201058/http://clerk.house.gov/member_info/electionInfo/index.html |archivedate=2008-07-30 |df= }}</ref><ref name=\"fedelect\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fec.gov/pubrec/electionresults.shtml|title=Election Results|publisher=[[Federal Election Commission]] |accessdate=}}</ref>\n! Year\n!\n! Republican\n! Votes\n! %\n!\n! Democratic\n! Votes\n! %\n!\n! Third Party\n! Party\n! Votes\n! %\n!\n|-\n|[[United States House election, 1986|1986]]\n||\n|{{party shading/Republican}} |'''Fred Upton'''\n|{{party shading/Republican}} |70,331\n|{{party shading/Republican}} |62%\n|\n|{{party shading/Democratic}} |Dan Roche\n|{{party shading/Democratic}} |41,624\n|{{party shading/Democratic}} |37%\n|\n|{{party shading/Independent}} |Richard Gillmor\n|{{Party shading/Independent}} |[[Independent (politician)|Independent]]\n|{{party shading/Independent}} |1,649\n|{{party shading/Independent}} |1%\n|<!--Write in 29-->\n|-\n|[[United States House election, 1988|1988]]\n||\n|{{party shading/Republican}} |'''Fred Upton'''\n|{{party shading/Republican}} |132,270\n|{{party shading/Republican}} |71%\n|\n|{{party shading/Democratic}} |Norman Rivers\n|{{party shading/Democratic}} |54,428\n|{{party shading/Democratic}} |29%\n|<!--Other 5-->\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[United States House election, 1990|1990]]\n||\n|{{party shading/Republican}} |'''Fred Upton'''\n|{{party shading/Republican}} |75,850\